The data set (“learning2014”) used in the following analyses is from an international survey of “Approaches to learning”, which was collected in 2014-2015. The original data contained 183 observations on several variables, but the data set used in the following analyses contains 166 observations on 7 variables; 17 observations that had a value of 0 on the variable “points”, were dropped out. The 7 variables include gender (a factor with two levels, “M” and “F”), age, attitude (reflecting global attitude towards statistics), points (exam points), and three numerical variables: deep, stra and surf, which reflect different learning strategies and attitudes (deep, surface, strategy). Deep, stra and surf have been composed of several sub-questions by taking a mean of all the relevant questions related to each of these scales.

The data includes 110 women and 56 men aged 17 to 55 years (the mean of age is 25.5 years and median 22 years, the distribution of age is positively skewed.) The ranges of other variables are 14-50 (attitude), 7-33 (points), 1.58-4.92 (deep), 1.25-5.00 (stra), 1.58-4.33 (surf). None of the variables seems to have normal distributions. There are moderate correlations between the variables that are statistically significant: attitude is positively correlated with points (r = 0.44). Also the different learning strategies and attitudes, deep, stra and surf, correlate significantly with each other: surf and deep have a negative correlation (r -0.32), and stra and surf also correlate negatively (r = -0.16). Surf and attitude also correlate negatively (r = -.18). There are no significant correlations between age and the other variables. There are some differences between men and women: in fact, surf and attitude correlate statistically significantly only in men (r = -0.37), and not in women (r = -0.02). Surf and deep also correlate actually in men (r = -0.62), but not in women (r = -0.09).

As stra is also left out of the model (as it was not a significant predictor of points), attitude is now the only predictor of points in the model. The estimate for the intercept is 11.64 (std error = 1.83), p = 1.95e-09, and the estimate for beta (attitude) is 0.35, std. error = 0.06, p = 4.12e-09. So, attitude is a significant predictor of points: when attitude is increased by one, points is increased by 0.35. The multiple R-squared of the model is 0.19, which means that 19% of the variation of points is explained by the variation of attitude.

plot(my_model3, which = c(1, 2, 5))

A linear regression model has the following assumptions: 1) linearity (there is a linear relationship between dependent and independent variables) 2) errors are normally distributed (with a mean of 0), not correlated , and have a constant variance

From the residuals vs. fitted values plot we can see that the errors have a mean close to 0 and that the variance is relatively constant. From the normal Q-Q plot we can see that the errors are quite well normally distributed, because they follow the dotted line. Although, there is some deviation from the line in both ends of the theoretical predicted values. From the residuals vs. leverage plot we can see that there are no clear outliers in the data, because the Cook’s distances for all residuals are very small (although they are scattered). I would say that the assumptions are adequately met.

The data used in the study is collected from two Portuguese schools, and it has been loaded from UCI Machine Learning Repository (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance). The data has been collected from school reports and with questionnaires, and it includes information on e.g. student achievement, family, activities, and alcohol use. There is a total of 370 students and information on 36 variables in the data.

Originally, there were two data sets, which provided information on two distinct subjects: mathematics and Portuguese. These data sets have been joined for this study, using common identifiers (variables that have the same values in both data sets, e.g. sex, age, address, family size etc.) The variables that had variation in the two data sets (e.g. the course grades), have been averaged.

The objective of this study is to analyze students’ alcohol consumption. Alcohol consumption is defined as “high” or “low”, and it is based on the average on weekday and weekend consumption (both were rated on a scale from 1 = very low to 5 = very high). If the total mean of weekday and weekend consumption is more than 2, then the participant is defined as a “high” user.

The hypothesis in this study are:

  1. sex: men are more often high users than women

  2. age (ranging from 15 to 22): older students are more often high users than younger students

  3. quality of family relationships (“famrel”, ranging from very bad 1 to excellent 5): bad family relationships are associated with high alcohol consumption

  4. current health status (“health”, ranging from very bad 1 to very good 5): good health is associated with low alcohol consumption

In sum, in this study we are going to study the relationship of four variables: sex, age, quality of family relationships and current health status, to alcohol consumption, defined as low/high consumption.

First, let’s explore the data and the distributions and relationships of these five variables in the study.

Let’s run a logistic regression analysis.

#Logistic regression analysis
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + age + famrel + health, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)

From the logistic regression analysis we can see, that three out of the four independent variables in the model are significantly associated with alcohol consumption (because the p-values related to their estimated coefficients are < 0.05). Sex, age and family relations are all significant predictors of high alcohol consumption, while health is not. Being a male and being older is associated with higher probability of high alcohol consumption, while having higher score on family relations is associated with lower probability of being a high user. From the odds ratios we can see, that men are 2.6 times more probable high users of alcohol than women. The odds ratio for age is also greater than 1 (1.3), which means that older age (in this data set) is associated with higher probability of being a high user of alcohol. The odds ratio for family relations is less than 1 (0.7), because having higher score on family relations was associated with lower probability of being a high user. The odds ratio for health is more than 1 (1.1), which means that higher scores on health are associated with higher probability of being a high user, but this variable was not a significant predictor (which can be also seen in the odds ratio confidence interval: the lower border is less than one while the upper border is over one). The results are in line with the hypothesis, except for the health variable: being a male, older age and lower scores on family relations were associated with higher probability of being a high user. It was hypothesized that also the health variable would be a significant predictor of alcohol use, but it was not. The relationship between the health variable and alcohol use was in the opposite direction than what was hypothesized, but, the association was not significant.

Exploring the predictive power of the model

# predict the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# see the last ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions
select(alc, age, famrel, health, sex, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.66486486 0.03513514 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.24594595 0.05405405 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.91081081 0.08918919 1.00000000
# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2810811

The predictive power of the model seems quite good, when we are predicting low users. From 259 students that are not high users of alcohol, the model predicts correctly 246. In the case of high users, the model does not work as well: it predicts correctly only 20 high users out of 111. This can be seen also in the graphic: in the “false” category there are clearly more red dots, which represent false predictions also by the model. But, in the “true” category, where there should have been more blue “true” dots, there is far more red dots than blue ones. In other words, the model does not predict high users very well, but it predicts quite well the low users. On average, 28% of the predictions the model makes, are false. In other words, 72% of the predictions are on average correct. So, the model is working better than chance! Because by simply guessing, 50% of the predictions would be correct on average, and 50% wrong.

The Boston data set contains information about housing in the area of Boston. The variables included are for example crime rate, nitrogen oxide concentration, teacher-pupil rate, and average number of rooms per dwelling. The data has 506 observations on 14 variables. Two of the variables are integers and the rest are numeric.

From the summaries and visual distributions we can see that many of the variables are very skewed. For example, the distributions of crim, zn, chas, nox, dis and lstat are positively skewed, and age, ptratio and black are negatively skewed. Some variables seem to have bimodal distributions, for example indus, rad and tax.

Correlations between study variables: Many of the study variables correlate with each other at least modestly. Strongest positive correlations (> 0.70) are found between rad and tax (r = 0.91), indus and nox (r = 0.76), nox and age (r = 0.73), indus and tax (r = 0.72), and rm and medv (r = 0.70). Strongest negative correlations (< -0.70) are found between nox and dis (r = -0.77), indus and dis (r = -0.71), age and dis (r = -0.75), and lstat and medv (r = -0.74).

Creating categorical variable of the crime rate variable and removing the continuous crim variable from the data. The new categorical crime variable has 4 categories: low, med_low, med_high and high.

# create a quantile vector of crim
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label=c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
# look at the table of the new factor crime
table(crime)

boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

Dividing the data to training set (80% of data) and test set (20% of data). The idea is to fit a linear discriminant analysis in the training data and than predict the classes in the test data in order to see how well the prediction works.

# number of rows in the Boston dataset 
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Next, let’s fit a linear discriminant analysis on the train data set using categorical crime variable as the target variable.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

From the plot it can be seen that the variable “rad” (index of accessibility to radial highways) is the most discriminative variable in the discriminant model. Other discriminative variables are nox (nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million) and zn (proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft). Perhaps all these variables are indicative of a bigger town?

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       18       7        1    0
##   med_low    7      18        5    0
##   med_high   0      11       15    1
##   high       0       0        0   19

The LDA model predicts very well the “high” cases: all the real “high” cases are predicted as “high” and there are only 2 med_high cases that has been predicted wrongly as “high”. Also the “med_low” cases are predicted pretty well: 14 out of 17 cases are predicted right. The model seems to have most problems with predicting the “low” class: 23 out of 34 cases have been predicted right.

Next, we will run k-means algorithm and investigate the optimal number of clusters in the data set. First, we will run the k-means with 3 clusters, and then we will investigate the optimal number of clusters using within cluster sum of squares (WCSS).

library("MASS")
#Standardizing the data set
boston_scaled2 <- scale(Boston)

# euclidean distance matrix
dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled2)

# the summary of the distances
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970
# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 3)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled2, col = km$cluster)

#Investigating the optimal number of clusters 
set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled2, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

The optimal number of clusters seems to be 2, because the value of total WCSS changes radically there. Let’s run the k-means with 2 clusters.

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled2, col = km$cluster)

The optimal way of clustering the Boston data is by using 2 clusters. The variable rad (index of accessibility to radial highways) seems to have an effect on the clustering as well as tax (full-value property-tax rate per $10,000) and zn (proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft).
